Preheat your oven to 200°C. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into roughly 1cm pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Cut the @cherry tomatoes{1} in half. Pick the thyme leaves from their stalks (discard the stalks).

Pop the tomatoes on a #baking tray{}, season with @salt{}, @ground black pepper{} and a pinch of @?sugar{pinch}. Roast on the top shelf of your oven for ~{10%minutes}. When done, remove from the oven and set aside.

Pop the kettle on to boil. Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the onion and season with a pinch of salt and a grind of black pepper. Cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Next add the garlic, @thyme{1/2%tsp}(leaves picked), @tomato purée{15%g} and @chorizo{1}(diced) to the pan. Give everything a good stir. Cook for another ~{2%minutes}. Add the @orzo{180%g} to the pan and stir again so it gets a good coating of all the other ingredients.

Add the boiling @water{400%ml} to the pan along with the @vegetable stock pot{1/2}. Stir to dissolve the stock pot. Simmer until the liquid has been absorbed and the orzo is tender, ~{8-9%minutes}.

> Stir occasionally to ensure nothing sticks to the bottom of the pan. If the liquid is all absorbed before the orzo is cooked, add another splash of water and give it a couple more mins.

While the orzo cooks, roughly tear the @mozzarella{1} into small pieces and grate the @parmesan cheese{20%g}. When the orzo is ready, take the pan off the heat, add the mozzarella, half the parmesan and the roasted tomatoes. Stir gently. Add the @baby spinach{1} on top and pop a #lid{} on the pan so the spinach wilts, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir it through.

Serve your orzo in bowls with the rest of the parmesan sprinkled on top. Enjoy!